2006.","meanings":["Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ivar</i>, from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. This is also an Americanized form of the rare Norwegian and Danish cognate <b>Ivarsen</b>. Compare   Iverson   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Iverson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Iver, Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Selmer, Thor, Evald, Gunner, Helmer, Ingman, Jarl, Joneen.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Iversen   and of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b> (see   Ivarson  ), all cognates of 2 below.","English (Kent and London): patronymic from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, <i>Iwar</i>, <i>Ivar</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. Alternatively, the name might be a patronymic from the Welsh male personal name <i>Ifor</i>, itself from British Celtic <i>Iūdomāros</i> ‘lord’ + ‘great’, but if so, it is not clear that it survives today."]}]},{"name":"Harald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Haraldr</i>, meaning ‘army leader’, cognate with English <b>Harold</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"“The","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>odal</i> ‘inherited property’ as the first element."],"variants":[{"name":"Utt","meanings":["From earlier <i>Uda</i>, a Germanic name meaning ‘heritage’; name of the mother of Kriemhild in the <i>Nibelungenlied</i>."]}]},{"name":"Black","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: chiefly from Middle English <i>blak(e)</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>, <i>blaca</i>), a nickname given from the earliest times to a swarthy or dark-haired man. However, Middle English <i>blac</i> also meant ‘pale, wan’, a reflex of Old English <i>blāc</i> ‘pale, white’ with a shortened vowel. Compare   Blatch   and   Blick  . With rare exceptions it is impossible to disambiguate these antithetical senses in Middle English surnames. The same difficulty arises with   Blake   and   Block  .","Scottish: in Gaelic-speaking areas this name was adopted as a translation of the epithet <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black-(haired)’, or of various other names based on Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘black’, see   Duff  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames directly or indirectly derived from the adjective meaning ‘black, dark’, for example German and Jewish   Schwarz   and Slavic surnames beginning with <i>Čern-</i>, <i>Chern-</i> (see   Chern   and   Cherne  ), <i>Chorn-</i>, <i>Crn-</i> or <i>Czern-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Blagg","meanings":["English: variant of   Black   with voicing of the final consonant."]},{"name":"Blake","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which has two quite distinct etymologies. It is both from Old English <i>blæc</i> ‘black’ and from Old English <i>blāc</i> ‘pale, white’ it was thus originally a nickname given to someone with hair or skin that was either remarkably dark or remarkably light. It is now quite popular as a boy's name."]},{"name":"Blackie","meanings":["Scottish: diminutive of   Black  .","English: nickname for a person with dark eyes, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>eie</i> ‘eye’ (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>ēage</i>)."]},{"name":"Blackson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the nickname or surname   Black   + <i>-son</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Block","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a nickname for someone resembling a badger (Middle English <i>broc(k)</i>, Old English <i>brocc</i>, of Celtic origin)."]},{"name":"Blacklock","meanings":["English (northern): nickname for someone with dark hair, from Middle English <i>blāk</i> + <i>lok(e)</i> (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>locc</i>), although <i>blāk</i> might mean either ‘dark’ or ‘fair’ (see   Black  ). The meaning ‘dark hair’ is the most probable since this name contrasts with   Whitlock  ."]},{"name":"Blatch","meanings":["English (Essex, but historically also in south and southwest England): nickname from Middle English <i>blache</i>, <i>bleche</i> ‘pale, pallid, of fair complexion’ (Old English <i>blǣce</i>)."]},{"name":"Blackett","meanings":["English:","nickname for a person with dark or fair hair, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>) or ‘fair’ (Old English <i>blāc</i>) + <i>hed</i>, <i>heved</i> ‘head’. See also   Black  .","nickname from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>hod</i> ‘hood’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Harald “The Black Svari” Ivarson was born in 1020, in Ireland as the son of Ímar MacArailt, King of Northumbria and Dublin. He had at least 1 son with Ragnfredsdater."},"et":{"1020–":"1020–Surnud","1020–Male":"1020–Surnud","–1095":"–1095","1020–Female":"1020–Surnud","1040–1095":"1040–1095","0995–1054":"0995–1054","about 1040":"umbes 1040","0995":"0995","1054":"1054","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1095":"1095","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Workington, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Workington, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1020–":"1020–Kuollut","1020–Male":"1020–Kuollut","–1095":"–1095","1020–Female":"1020–Kuollut","1040–1095":"1040–1095","0995–1054":"0995–1054","about 1040":"noin 1040","0995":"0995","1054":"1054","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1095":"1095","Ireland":"Irlanti","Workington, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Workington, Cumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1020–":"1020–Décédé","1020–Male":"1020–Décédé","–1095":"–1095","1020–Female":"1020–Décédée","1040–1095":"1040–1095","0995–1054":"099